I. About This Project¶

In This Project, From The NFT Collection Dataset (https://www.kaggle.com/nenamalikah/nft-collections-by-sales-volume), I want to do the Exploratory Data Analysis about it using Data Manipulation Libraries such as Numpy, Pandas, and Plotly. The goal of this project is I want to Give Insights from the dataset about the NFT Stats, so after you reading this you will gain informations from the report provided about the NFT.

For Related Libraries Documentations that I used in this project, you can access through this link :

  • Numpy : https://numpy.org/
  • Pandas : https://pandas.pydata.org/
  • Plotly : https://plotly.com/

II. What is EDA?¶

Exploratory Data Analysis refers to the critical process of performing initial investigations on data so as to discover patterns,to spot anomalies,to test hypothesis and to check assumptions with the help of summary statistics and graphical representations. (source = https://towardsdatascience.com/exploratory-data-analysis-8fc1cb20fd15)

III. Plan of Attack¶

In this project, There are 2 Major Steps in order to get the result using CNN, which are :

  • Data Wrangling & Cleaning
  • Visualize the Data with Plotly

Step 1 : Data Wrangling & Cleaning¶

In this step, I will transform the dataset that I got from Kaggle into a new form that we will visualize later. Here, I use Pandas and Numpy as the main libraries for this step.

Part 1 : Import Libraries¶

I Imported Libraries that I need for this project, Which are :

  • Numpy : for working with arrays and numerical operation
  • Pandas : for data manipulation and analysis (also data cleaning)
  • Cufflinks : for connects plotly with pandas
  • plotly.express : provides functions to visualize a variety of types of data
  • chart_studio.plotly : provides a web-service for hosting graphs
  • plotly.offline : generate graphs offline and save them
In [1]:
#import libraries
%matplotlib inline
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import cufflinks as cf
import chart_studio.plotly as py
import plotly.express as px
from plotly.offline import download_plotlyjs, init_notebook_mode, plot, iplot
init_notebook_mode(connected = True)
cf.go_offline()

There you go. Lets move on to the next step, Visualize the Data with Plotly

Step 2 : Visualize the Data with Plotly¶

In this step, we will use Plotly for visualize the dataset. we will gain many insights from this tool. but before we start, What is Plotly, actually?

Part 1 : Plotly¶

Plotly is an open-source library that provides a list of chart types as well as tools with callbacks to make a dashboard. The charts which I have embedded here are all made in chart studio of plotly. It helps to embed charts easily anywhere you want.

The main plus point of plotly is its interactive nature and of course visual quality. Plotly is in great demand rather than other libraries like Matplotlib and Seaborn. Plotly provides a list of charts having animations in 1D, 2D, and 3D too. (source = https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/2021/06/tricks-for-data-visualization-plotly-library/)

Part 2 : Bar Chart¶

A bar chart or bar graph is a chart or graph that presents categorical data with rectangular bars with heights or lengths proportional to the values that they represent. The bars can be plotted vertically or horizontally. A vertical bar chart is sometimes called a column chart. In this project I will Make Bar Charts which are comparison of :

  • Volume of Top 10 NFT on the market in Solana
  • Volume of Top 10 NFT on the market in United States Dollar
  • Market Cap of Top 10 NFT in Solana
  • Market Cap of Top 10 NFT in United States Dollar

Related Documentation :

  • https://plotly.com/python/bar-charts/
In [8]:
df_top10 = df_new.head(10)

fig = px.bar(df_top10, 
             x = 'Name',
             y = 'Volume',
             text = 'Volume',
             color = 'Name',
             title = 'Comparison of Volume of Top 10 NFT on the market in Solana',
             labels = {'Volume' : 'Volume', 'Name' : 'NFT Name'})
fig.update_traces(texttemplate = '%{text:.3s}', textposition = 'outside')
fig.update_layout(uniformtext_minsize = 9)
fig.update_layout(xaxis_tickangle =-45)
fig.update_layout(yaxis_range = [0,35000])

fig.show(renderer='notebook_connected')

Conclusion :

  1. Total Volume comparison in Solana and USD is very linear and base.market still lead with a total of 27.3k in Solana and 4M in USD
  2. The total market cap is very uneven. IM AIKO leads the total market cap in the top 10 NFT with 2.53k in Solana and 372k in USD. while the Top 10 NFT with the lowest market cap is the Meerkat Millionaires Country Club with 90.3 in Solana and 13.3k in USD.

Part 3 : Histogram¶

A histogram is a graphical representation that organizes a group of data points into user-specified ranges. Similar in appearance to a bar graph, the histogram condenses a data series into an easily interpreted visual by taking many data points and grouping them into logical ranges or bins.In this project I made 2 Histograms, which are :

  • Distribution Number of NFT Owners
  • Distribution Number of NFT Assets

Related Documentation :

  • https://plotly.com/python/histograms/
In [12]:
fig = px.histogram(df, x="Owners", title = 'Distribution of NFT Owners')
fig.show(renderer='notebook_connected')
In [13]:
fig = px.histogram(df, x="Assets", title = 'Distribution of NFT Assets', color_discrete_sequence = ['green'])
fig.show(renderer='notebook_connected')

Conclusion :

  1. There are about 462 types of NFT that have owners from a range of 0-49 people. Meanwhile, only 1 NFT has 2000+ owners
  2. There are around 335 types of NFTs with assets ranging from 0-49 people. Meanwhile, only 8 NFTs have assets of more than 1000

Part 4 : Scatter Plot¶

A scatter plot (aka scatter chart, scatter graph) uses dots to represent values for two different numeric variables. The position of each dot on the horizontal and vertical axis indicates values for an individual data point. Scatter plots are used to observe relationships between variables. I made 2 Plots which are :

  • The relation between Sales and Owners
  • The relation between USD Floor Price and USD Average Price

Related Documentation :

  • https://plotly.com/python/line-and-scatter/
In [14]:
fig = px.scatter(df_new,
           x = 'Sales',
           y = 'Owners',
           color = 'Category',
           size = 'Assets',
           hover_data = ['Owner_Asset_Ratio'],
           title = 'The relation between Sales and Owners')

fig.show(renderer='notebook_connected')
In [15]:
fig = px.scatter(df_new,
           x = 'Floor_Price_USD',
           y = 'Average_Price_USD',
           color = 'Category',
           title = 'The relation between USD Floor Price and USD Average Price')
fig.update_layout(yaxis_range = [0,15000])

fig.show(renderer='notebook_connected')

Conclusions:

  • On average, NFT has Owners in the 0-500 range and total sales in the 0-2000 range. Meanwhile, the Collectibles category has the highest Owners and Sales with 2041 owners and 4980 sales and an owner asset ratio of 61%.
  • The average NFT has an average price in the range of 0-2000 usd and a floor price in the range of 0-6000 usd. The Collectibles, Digital, Privilege category has the highest average price of 10kusd and the Metaverse category, Collectibles has the highest floor price of 60k usd
